Dashaa <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/bdrinal28133.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balrak>Balrak</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><font color=#FF0000>Drinal Ally</font></span><br>  Posts: 467<br> <font color=#FF0000>(11/27/02 7:37:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1703.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: LOL</span><hr size=1> In my days of gaming and guilding I have rarely if ever charged anyone in my guild for an item I had. I would actually say I never but there may of been an occasion 3 years ago where I desperately needed cash to buy peridots, but that would of been the only time and as I said I still don't recall doing this.<br>
<br>
So my question to you all is this, why do you join a guild? To be a close knit group of friends that some would like call your &quot;online family&quot;. So why have this family? Well I was always under the impression you founded or joined a guild to better not only yourself but those around you. You assist each other, you give what you can to those who need without the thought of payment or expectations other than they do the same when they are asked by a lower lvl in the future. <br>
<br>
Now apparently the younger generations of people and a few of the older ones have never heard of the concept of taking care of family. This isn't something that's taught in the game, rather at home outside of the game. It's quite basic so let me break it down for those of you who are jaded by this theory. <br>
<br>
If someone in your guild needs and item and you have it, well it's your duty to help them. Greed is a powerful tool of the dark side *yes it's a yoda thing* and overtime that greed will overcome your entire guild and destroy any principles you once had. Disputes erupt, hate towards others occurs, the lack of confidence grows within the guild, and lastly an entire breakdown of all standards and morals occurs ala guild disbandment.<br>
<br>
I’ve never was rich in eq and I never will be, but does this bother me so? Absolutely not; in fact I take pride in saying I do things not out of personal gain, but for the pure enjoyment of helping others who needed it. Surprising to some this explanation may be, to others you may feel its more propaganda, but to those of you who believe this then it's only you yourselves you’re kidding and misleading the masses. I could name a handful of you right now who did this in the past, you know who you are, I know who you are and we both know your immoral attitude towards others is a conflict of personal interest between us, which in the end hurts you more than it will ever hurt me.<br>
<br>
Now dealing with others outside the guild is different, you of course can and should charge for services rendered, but to do so with mates is wrong, period. Greedy people will only end up in one place after a period of time, by themselves on a cold dark alley moaning.<br>
<br>
This is not picking on the above named guild, but as a general rule of thumb this is a value system I have always adopted in my guilds and those I joined, it works well if monitored to do so.<br>
<br>
<br>
